 <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://mywebpages.comcast.net/sammigayle/jeol/SigPic-Pyro.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=eloinapyromancer>Eloina Pyromancer</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Master Summoner</span><br>  Posts: 455<br> <font color=#333333>(2/24/03 6:00:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1869.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Summoned Weapons...</span><hr size=1> Summoned weapons are needed to enable dual-wield in pets prior to 39 (is it 34 now with max level pets?).  From 24-39, give your pets two summoned weapons to allow them to hit more often.<br>
<br>
After that, only give them summoned weapons if you need to.  i.e. sword of runes vs summoned creatures, or if you need to boost elemental's MR with daggers of symbols, etc.<br>
<br>
The ornate cutlasses are the Blade of Walnan, available at level 61.  They proc a magic-based damage spell.  If you have those available, they work well :-)  There are other summoned weapons post-60... Fist of Ixiblat and Blade of the Kedge... they proc a fire and cold based DD respectively.<br>
<br>
Other weapons that mages give to pets usually have a stun proc, al la gnoll hide whips.  An air pet with two gnoll hide whips will usually keep its opponent stunned a good proportion of time.<br>
<br>
Pets bash whether or not they have a shield equipped.  Actually, equipping a shield reduces the amount of damage a dual-wielding pet does... quite noticeable at higher levels when off hand swings happen more often.  Never give a shield to a pet capable of dual wielding -- you'll be reducing the amount of damage that he does.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=artulyn1>Artulyn1</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/anim_1.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Arch Mage</span><br>  Posts: 426<br> <font color=#333333>(2/25/03 9:24:12 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerspells.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1869.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://mysite.verizon.net/res0qqnm/sitebuildercontent/sitebuilderpictures/artulyn-tag.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Summoned Weapons...</span><hr size=1> Yes they changed the weapon delay affecting NPCs a while back (about two years ago). Seems that necros were equipping their pets with dual FS daggers or daggers of symbols and their pets would do amazing amounts of damage because NPC damage can only be raised with weapons, if a weapons max damage is lower than the NPCs intrinsic max damage, the NPC will use it's own damage. However since, at the time, NPCs would take on the speed of a weapon the DPS of necro pets was just incredable and they could chew up mages fairly easily. Please note that at this time mage pets were broken because they did not dual wield like they were supposed to do. Part of the fix to mage pets resulted in this change of NPC weapon speed behavior, another part was giving mage pets the ability to use weapons.<br>
<br>
Some people also used to use this feature (before it was changed) to take out the Priest of Discord by giving it dual orc pawn picks, which are some of the slowest weapons in the game. The combination of the large weapon delay and slows made him relatively easy to take out.<br>
<br>
